Another nice thing about this caliber is that nothing else on this rifle needs to be changed to allow it fire the 5.56 ammo other than the barrel. Everything else is the same including the magazines. Really want a great package buy another upper receiver and parts kit attach the 5.56 Barrel and now you can quick change from the .300 blackout to the 5.56 in just a few seconds. Pull the 2 take down pins and swap out the completed uppers and away you go. That simple, that quick.

title: For Sale/Trade:  By all means, if you are offended, flag it.
postcontent:
Good day, good evening, good whatever. I write this knowing full well that there are plenty of good, intelligent and logical men and women out there that are looking to buy, sell or trade their weapons on this wonderful website. To those people I truly wish you the best in your search for the perfect weapon, whatever that may be. As soon as I can find two pistols duct taped to a rifle duct taped to a flame thrower, I will count myself among those that have found the perfect gun. Unfortunately there are some real dumbasses out there. Maybe calling these people dumbasses is a little much but overkill is under rated. And the people that post some of the bullshit that goes up on this site deserve to be called that. A spade is a spade after all. 

Why the hell is everyone so damn vague with their postings? I swear that some of these seem like you started a post, made a ham sandwich, ate said sandwich and then came back to the post but couldn't quite remember what you were thinking in the first place. If your posting title says you want a 9mm, 40, 45 or 380, please remember that when you write that you only want a high caliber shooting handgun and don't want anything less than a 9mm. Last I checked a 380 was smaller than a 9 so take the additional two seconds it takes to do some damn proof reading. And don't get all over zealous with what you want because a 9mm isn't exactly a high caliber round there genius. 

What deserves to be described with the word "custom". If you put a few things that you picked up at your local gun store on your rifle or pistol and it did not require a professional in any way, or you are not a professional gunsmith yourself, then you do not have an item that should be called custom. A fucking glock with a high cap magazine or a piece of shit NC Star laser does not qualify your gun as something that is, or probably ever will be, custom. Just because it's custom to you does not mean it's custom to the rest of the gun community. "One of a kind", "decked out", "tricked out" and countless other descriptive terms should be stricken as well. Unless you know for a fact that your gun is in fact one of a kind, don't say that shit. Do some research before you go all out over-exaggerating what you've got.  God only knows how many "one of a kind" straight from the factory rifles there are out there but I'm willing to bet that there are way more than your taking credit for.

Sniper scopes. Jesus Christ, there is no such thing as a sniper scope. Only when a scope is mounted to a weapon that is in the hands of an actual trained sniper could your scope be considered a sniper scope. We get it, your really great at sniping digital terrorists in call of duty or you hit a target that was really far away that one time, but if your not a sniper then you don't have a sniper scope. Just say what you've got and let that be that. Not need to try to make what you have sound cooler than what it is. Most of the people reading your ad have a google search page opened up to see what it is anyway so chances are they will figure it out. If your not a sniper do not use sniper as a description for your gun or optics.

To go along with "sniper rifles" and "sniper scopes", the word "tactical" is getting a little fucking ridiculous. Just because you saw it in a movie being used by a military bad ass, your weapon is just a weapon. How it is employed makes it tactical. The other day I read an ad for a "tactical" airsoft gun and wanted to punch through my living room windows for that genius display of dumb ass adjective word association. If your not using your gun to clear rooms, breach doorways or any other activity that would need a tactical approach, then drop the word tactical from the description. 

Over pricing. Seriously, I understand wanting to make money, but come the fuck on. I saw a guy post a Sig rifle that retails brand new almost 1000 less than what he initially posted it for. This website is intended to help people network to find guns they want, not to pad your wallet. Just because there's some idiot out there that will pay too much for something doesn't mean they should. It's borderline unethical to take advantage of the people out there that either don't know any better or don't care about spending more money than they should. 

While the world is riddled with all sorts of problems, this site usually offers far more solutions than problems. If I offended you, well, I don't apologize because you probably fit into one of the previously mentioned categories and you need to learn how to post an ad on this site. That or you need to stop over compensating for what you have. To anyone that I've enlightened or anyone that expresses the same feelings as I do then I hope this benefits each and everyone of you. Even the people that want to talk up their "one of a kind, tricked out, tactical custom AR15 sniper rifle" because every sniper in the world knows that something that shoots .223 is a real game changer in the sniper community. 

If you are offended by any of this then you probably posted some dumb shit up here at one point or another and this just makes you realize how dumb it was in the first place and for that I do not apologize. I apologize to everyone that had to read it in the first place. Please everyone, help make a change. Thanks

title: For Sale/Trade:  By all means, if you are offended, flag it.
postcontent:
Good day, good evening, good whatever. I write this knowing full well that there are plenty of good, intelligent and logical men and women out there that are looking to buy, sell or trade their weapons on this wonderful website. To those people I truly wish you the best in your search for the perfect weapon, whatever that may be. As soon as I can find two pistols duct taped to a rifle duct taped to a flame thrower, I will count myself among those that have found the perfect gun. Unfortunately there are some real dumbasses out there. Maybe calling these people dumbasses is a little much but overkill is under rated. And the people that post some of the bullshit that goes up on this site deserve to be called that. A spade is a spade after all. 

Why the hell is everyone so damn vague with their postings? I swear that some of these seem like you started a post, made a ham sandwich, ate said sandwich and then came back to the post but couldn't quite remember what you were thinking in the first place. If your posting title says you want a 9mm, 40, 45 or 380, please remember that when you write that you only want a high caliber shooting handgun and don't want anything less than a 9mm. Last I checked a 380 was smaller than a 9 so take the additional two seconds it takes to do some damn proof reading. And don't get all over zealous with what you want because a 9mm isn't exactly a high caliber round there genius. 

What deserves to be described with the word "custom". If you put a few things that you picked up at your local gun store on your rifle or pistol and it did not require a professional in any way, or you are not a professional gunsmith yourself, then you do not have an item that should be called custom. A fucking glock with a high cap magazine or a piece of shit NC Star laser does not qualify your gun as something that is, or probably ever will be, custom. Just because it's custom to you does not mean it's custom to the rest of the gun community. "One of a kind", "decked out", "tricked out" and countless other descriptive terms should be stricken as well. Unless you know for a fact that your gun is in fact one of a kind, don't say that shit. Do some research before you go all out over-exaggerating what you've got.  God only knows how many "one of a kind" straight from the factory rifles there are out there but I'm willing to bet that there are way more than your taking credit for.

Sniper scopes. Jesus Christ, there is no such thing as a sniper scope. Only when a scope is mounted to a weapon that is in the hands of an actual trained sniper could your scope be considered a sniper scope. We get it, your really great at sniping digital terrorists in call of duty or you hit a target that was really far away that one time, but if your not a sniper then you don't have a sniper scope. Just say what you've got and let that be that. Not need to try to make what you have sound cooler than what it is. Most of the people reading your ad have a google search page opened up to see what it is anyway so chances are they will figure it out. If your not a sniper do not use sniper as a description for your gun or optics.

To go along with "sniper rifles" and "sniper scopes", the word "tactical" is getting a little fucking ridiculous. Just because you saw it in a movie being used by a military bad ass, your weapon is just a weapon. How it is employed makes it tactical. The other day I read an ad for a "tactical" airsoft gun and wanted to punch through my living room windows for that genius display of dumb ass adjective word association. If your not using your gun to clear rooms, breach doorways or any other activity that would need a tactical approach, then drop the word tactical from the description. 

Over pricing. Seriously, I understand wanting to make money, but come the fuck on. I saw a guy post a Sig rifle that retails brand new almost 1000 less than what he initially posted it for. This website is intended to help people network to find guns they want, not to pad your wallet. Just because there's some idiot out there that will pay too much for something doesn't mean they should. It's borderline unethical to take advantage of the people out there that either don't know any better or don't care about spending more money than they should. 

While the world is riddled with all sorts of problems, this site usually offers far more solutions than problems. If I offended you, well, I don't apologize because you probably fit into one of the previously mentioned categories and you need to learn how to post an ad on this site. That or you need to stop over compensating for what you have. To anyone that I've enlightened or anyone that expresses the same feelings as I do then I hope this benefits each and everyone of you. Even the people that want to talk up their "one of a kind, tricked out, tactical custom AR15 sniper rifle" because every sniper in the world knows that something that shoots .223 is a real game changer in the sniper community. 

If you are offended by any of this then you probably posted some dumb shit up here at one point or another and this just makes you realize how dumb it was in the first place and for that I do not apologize. I apologize to everyone that had to read it in the first place. Please everyone, help make a change. Thanks

title: For Sale:  30 rds 5.56 NATO .223 AR15 AR-15  M-193 Ammo Lake City Federal 55 gr brass
postcontent:
30 rds 5.56x45 XM-193 55 gr. Lake City Federal ammo manufacture date of Oct 2012. That is exactly one 30 rd magazine worth of the best ammo you could feed an AR15! These are the exact same rounds the US ARMY usesI  Except, in most cases they use the 62 gr. M-855 which has the steel penetrator. That's because they are in a fight where the enemy might have body armor. But most people aren't looking for something to penetrate armor - they are looking for something that will kill a badguy. The M-193 is the best round for that task. I just happened to buy a few thousand rounds a couple of months before this whole thing kicked off. But now, there's a whole lot of guys who have new rifles, new magazines, but no ammo. I will sell you some of my stockpile. It's going to be (pre freak out) expensive. But since you can't get any 5.56/.223 ammo anywhere, this is a bargain. I just want to see EVERYONE able to load up now. No sense owning a rifle and not having any ammo. I will not sell my entire stash. BTW, you should have prepared earlier. But then again, isn't that always the case...

Just in case you are new to owning AR15s, check your barrel and make sure it is stamped either 5.56 or 5.56/.223. If all you see is .223 - Then do not buy this ammo. Although it probably won't kill you, you should not shoot 5.56 through a .223 only barrel.

postcontent:
I am looking to sell  (Connecticut AWB compliant Railed Post - Ban Model)

Chambered in 5.45x39.

This is one of the best AK’s ever sold in the United States. These rifles were factory built by “Arsenal of Bulgaria” on Russian tooling in Bulgaria as original AK-74 (not as a single stock sportier-carbine like Saiga or Vepr). They required minimal modification (not to be completely converted as Saiga) by “Arsenal of USA” in Las Vegas, to be compliant with 922 (r). These rifles are meet criteria to be considered “Made in the USA.” The USA manufactured parts are counted towards compliance of 922 (r), allowing the sale and possession of the original, un-importable configuration. They include: the stock, pistol grip, upper handguard, lower handguard, trigger, forged hammer, disconnector and double stage trigger. The USA made disconnector and double stage trigger eliminated any feeling of “trigger slap” common in many AK’s. Barrel is chrome lined.  

This rifle has black Tapco polymer furniture, the side optic rail and 10.5 inches NATO length stock (can be easily replaced by a shorter "Warsaw Pact" standard stock). The stock has a spring-loaded trap door in the rear to accommodate a cleaning kit. The correct - 74 style break was properly installed (pinned and welded) in accordance to CT AWB by a professional gunsmith.

I bought this rifle several years ago. The gun was hardly used before me. I've fired only 90 trouble free rounds through the rifle and took great care of it. This is a very clean rifle in an excellent condition. 

This rifle comes with sling, butt stock cleaning kit and one 30rd mag with 60 rounds, Please note that new circle10’s mags are still available on-line for $39.99.

5.45x39 is a very effective round. It is still (and will be) a LOT cheaper than .223 or 7.62x39

This is a rare ORIGINAL AK-74 rifle. My price is $2000. Please, do not contact me if you feel that that price is very unreasonable. I do not care if you decided not to pay “panic price”. I paid for that rifle more then for Colt M-4 carbine. I am sure that upcoming ban will change your opinion. I will respond to serious offers. Please, e-mail your phone number.

I will sell FTF in Hartford or close by to a CT resident. MUST BE OVER 21 YEARS OLD with a VALID CT DL (prefer CT Pistol Permit) and be willing to sign a BILL OF SALE. Out of state to your FFL ONLY. They must provide a copy of a FFL. They must accept firearm shipment from a private party.

title: For Sale:  Engraved 1861 Colt Navy Presentation Revolver
postcontent: Fully Engraved 1861 Colt Navy presentation Revolver 36 caliber, very early serial number 9765. I am selling this gun on consignment. It is out of an old Indian Trading Post from Gallup, New Mexico where it has been stored in a vault for over 25 years. This gun is in superb (museum quality) condition. The gun is silver plated and fully engraved by Gustave Young who was Colt's premier engraver from the 1850s through the 1870s. He is often referred to as the Picasso of engravers. His "signature" mark is the dog/wolf head show here in. The gun's grips are ivory and it has all matching serial numbers. This gun was obviously a custom order gun made as a presentation piece. The back of the back strap was left blank where a persons name would have been engraved . I have been told the Confederacy ordered a small number of these Navy models at the beginning of the civil war to be used as presentation pieces. Because the serial number fits in that same time period it has been suggested that this could very well be one of those pieces? While we know very little about the history of this gun we do know it is extremely rare to find a silver plated Gustave Young engraved presentation gun for sale in this kind of condition.  It can be shipped registered mail but only after , approval and payment has been made.. Email me with any questions.
